[1] Ukraine
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2018 23:27
Source: 112 UA [edited]
https://112.international/society/situation-with-measles-stabilized-in-ukraine-ministry-of-health-26071.html


The situation with measles in Ukraine has stabilized, although it is too early to say about reducing the incidence rate. This was announced at a briefing by the director of the Center for Public Health of the Ministry of Health Volodymyr Kurpita. He noted that from [Mon 19 - Sun 25 Feb 2018] nearly 800 people became ill with measles in Ukraine: 294 adults and 489 children. This is 5 per cent less than last week [week ending Sun 18 Feb 2018].

"We can state that the situation with the measles in Ukraine has stabilized, we are not talking about reducing the incidence, but about stabilizing the process," he said. According to Kurpita, since the beginning of the year [2018], 5839 Ukrainians [have been] ill with measles: 1981 adults and 3857 children. Almost 4000 patients [have been] hospitalized.

Over the past week [week of Sun 18 Feb 2018], the 7th case of death was reported due to complications from measles in 2018. This was a newborn child in the Odesa region, who lived only a few hours after birth.

In 2017, the level of routine vaccination has doubled compared with 2016. Up to 93.3 per cent of children under one year old and 90.7 per cent of 6 year old children were vaccinated.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[According to 2016 data from the World Health Organization (WHO), Ukraine ranks lowest in terms of vaccination coverage in Europe. At the end of 2016, fewer than 50 per cent of one year olds had been vaccinated against measles.

The solution sounds easy; parents need to immunise their children against this deadly disease, it's the only way to be protected. But in Ukraine, the problem is always more complicated.

Low levels of coverage are the result not only of parents' choice but of limited availability of vaccines over the past 7 years. In addition, the myths about vaccination as being potentially harmful, and the lack of consultation among parents and health workers, meant that Ukraine's coverage against measles dramatically dropped from 97 per cent in 2007 to 42 per cent in 2016.

UNICEF has delivered vaccines at the request of the Ministry of Health since 2016.

The positive news is that the trend shows parents are more inclined to vaccinate their children today than 9 years ago. More than 76 per cent of parents now support vaccination in Ukraine. Surveys also prove that as parents are better informed about the risks of diseases, they are more likely to support vaccination. But we still need to do better.

Excerpted and edited from https://blogs.unicef.org/blog/sad-inevitability-of-measles-in-ukraine/.

A Healthmap of Ukraine can be found at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5663849,123. - Mod.LK]

